---
import ServicePageLayout from '../layouts/ServicePageLayout.astro';

const faqSchemaObject = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should I service my furnace?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Annual maintenance is recommended, ideally in fall before heating season. This prevents mid-winter breakdowns."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does heating maintenance include?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Inspect heat exchanger, clean burners, check gas pressure, test safety controls, lubricate motors, and replace air filters."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can maintenance prevent carbon monoxide leaks?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — we inspect the heat exchanger for cracks during every maintenance visit, which is critical for preventing CO leaks."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<ServicePageLayout
  title="Heating Maintenance in Stanton, CA | Hilo Heating and Air"
  description="Professional heating maintenance and seasonal tune-ups in Stanton, CA. Prevent breakdowns and keep your furnace running efficiently."
  heroTitle="Heating Maintenance in Stanton, CA"
  heroSubtitle="Most furnaces don't quit without warning. They give signs first. Staying ahead of that is the whole point of HVAC maintenance service."
  faqSchema={faqSchemaObject}
>
  <section class="pt-4 sm:pt-8 pb-16 sm:pb-24 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 prose prose-lg">
      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-brand-blue mt-0 mb-4">Why Regular Heating Maintenance Pays Off</h2>

      <p>Most furnaces don't quit without warning. They give signs first — weaker airflow, odd smells when they kick on, a pilot light that flickers more than it used to. People ignore all of it until the system dies on the one cold morning of the year. Staying ahead of that is the whole point of <strong>HVAC maintenance service</strong>, and it costs a fraction of what an emergency repair runs. Hilo Heating and Air has kept furnaces and heat pumps running across Stanton for years, and the systems we check regularly almost never end up as panic calls in January.</p>

      <h2>Why It's Worth Doing</h2>
      <p>Nothing's wrong, so why pay for a check-up? Fair question, and the wrong instinct. By the time something's obviously broken, you've usually already missed the cheap fix. Routine <strong>HVAC maintenance service</strong> catches the small problems before they become the expensive ones — a worn igniter, a dirty filter choking airflow, electrical connections starting to corrode. None of it sounds urgent until it suddenly is.</p>
      <p>A typical visit covers the stuff most homeowners never check themselves. We test ignition systems, inspect heat exchangers for cracks (a real safety issue, not just an efficiency one), check thermostat accuracy, clean components, and look over ductwork for leaks that are quietly costing you money every month. Boring work, mostly. But it's the difference between a furnace that lasts fifteen years and one that limps to year eight.</p>

      <h2>Timing Changes Everything</h2>
      <p>Here's where people get it backwards. Heating maintenance shouldn't happen whenever you remember — it should happen right before the season actually needs it. That's <strong>seasonal HVAC maintenance</strong>: a fall check before the cold sets in, not a scramble in December when every HVAC company in Orange County already has a waitlist.</p>
      <p><strong>Seasonal HVAC maintenance</strong> also means catching problems while it's still mild outside, not freezing. We've had customers book a tune-up in October over something minor and completely avoid a breakdown by January. Small effort, real payoff — and honestly, it's the easiest way to avoid a no-heat emergency call altogether.</p>

      <h2>What a Visit Actually Looks Like</h2>
      <p>A technician shows up, runs through the full checklist, and explains anything found in plain language — not a sales pitch dressed up as a diagnosis. If everything checks out, we'll say so. We're not in the business of manufacturing problems to pad an invoice. If something's worth watching but doesn't need fixing yet, we'll flag it and let you decide on your own timeline.</p>

      <h2>Why Hilo Heating and Air</h2>
      <p>We built our name in Stanton by being straightforward — show up when we say we will, tell you the truth about what's actually wrong. Our technicians are licensed, insured, and trained to catch things most homeowners would never notice on their own. Whether it's a single visit or a standing maintenance plan, every system gets the same level of attention.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</ServicePageLayout>
